, Germany, to determine the winner of [[2011 FIFA Women's World Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.soccernation.com/japan-vs-sweden-update-japan-wins-and-will-face-usa-in-world-cup-final-cms-1489 |title=Japan vs Sweden Update: Japan Wins and Will Face USA in World Cup Final |access-date=13 July 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717005832/http://www.soccernation.com/japan-vs-sweden-update-japan-wins-and-will-face-usa-in-world-cup-final-cms-1489 |archive-date=17 July 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> It was played between [[Japan women's national football team|Japan]] and the [[United States women's national soccer team|United States]]. Japan won 3-1 on a [[penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shoot-out]] following a 2\u20132 draw after [[Extra time (association football)|extended time]], becoming the first [[Asian Football Confederation|Asian]] team to win a FIFA World Cup final.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/matches/round=255989/match=300144437/summary.html|title=Japan edge USA for maiden title|date=17 July 2011|work=[[FIFA]]|accessdate=17 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsfeed.time.com/2011/07/17/japan-beats-u-s-in-thrilling-womens-world-cup-final/|title=Japan Beats U.S. in Thrilling Women's World Cup Final|date=17 May 2011|work=Time|accessdate=18 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://proxy.espn.go.com/espnw/news-opinion/6777475/women-world-cup-team-destiny-turns-japan|title=Team of destiny turns out to be Japan|date=17 May 2011|work=ESPN|accessdate=18 July 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720184217/http://proxy.espn.go.com/espnw/news-opinion/6777475/women-world-cup-team-destiny-turns-japan|archive-date=20 July 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2011/jul/17/usa-japan-live-world-cup-final|title=USA v Japan - as it happened|date=17 May 2011|work=Guardian|accessdate=18 July 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110717220139/http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2011/jul/17/usa-japan-live-world-cup-final| archivedate= 17 July 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nThe 2011 final was the last major sporting event to be broadcast in Japan prior to the country's [[digital television transition|digital switchover]] that took place on 24 July 2011.\n\n==Background==\nThe match was between the [[United States women's national soccer team|United States]] (USA), which had been a major power in [[women's association football]] since winning the [[1991 FIFA Women's World Cup|inaugural World Cup championship]], and [[Japan women's national football team|Japan]], which had never won a major world title, or indeed even reached the finals of a major world competition. This was also the first appearances of the United States in the final after 12 years. The United States was bidding to become the first team to win a third world championship, having won in [[1991 FIFA Women's World Cup|1991]] and [[1999 FIFA Women's World Cup|1999]].<ref>[http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/football/womens-world-cup/france-usa-369193.html Women's World Cup \u2013 USA see off France to reach final]</ref> Japan became the fourth team to win a world championship, joining the United States, [[Norway women's national football team|Norway]] and [[Germany women's national football team|Germany]].\n\nThe match was the third between the two teams in World Cup play. The United States beat Japan 3\u20130 in pool play in 1991, and won 4\u20130 in a [[1995 FIFA Women's World Cup|1995]] quarterfinal match. Going into the final, the USA had never lost to Japan, with 22 wins and 3 draws.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/sports/soccer/news/_/id/6766720/women-world-cup-abby-wambach-become-ultimate-warrior-david-hirshey |title=Just call her Air Wambach |first=David |last=Hirshey |work=[[ESPN.com]] |date=14 July 2011 |accessdate=15 July 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110714140042/http://espn.go.com/sports/soccer/news/_/id/6766720/women-world-cup-abby-wambach-become-ultimate-warrior-david-hirshey| archivedate= 14 July 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref> Prior to the World Cup, the United States was the top-ranked team in the [[FIFA Women's World Rankings]], while Japan was ranked fourth.<ref>[https://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/ranking/lastranking/gender=f/fullranking.html FIFA/Coca-Cola Women's World Ranking]</ref>\n\nThis marked the first time that a team won the World Cup having lost a match in pool play.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/soccer/news?slug=ycn-8777149|title=Quarterfinal losses open door for World Cup history: A fan\u2019s take}}</ref>\n\nJapan became only the second [[Asian Football Confederation|Asian]] national team to reach the FIFA Women's World Cup Final, following [[China women's national football team|China]]'s final appearance against the United States in 1999. This was also only the second final not involving a [[UEFA|European]] team.\n\n==Route to the final==\n{|  style=\"width:100%; text-align:center;\"\n|-  style=\"vertical-align:top; background:#9cf;\"\n!colspan=2 style=\"width:1*\"|Japan\n!Round\n!colspan=2 style=\"width:1*\"|United States\n|- valign=\"top\" bgcolor=\"#c1e0ff\"\n|Opponent\n|Result\n||[[2011 FIFA Women's World Cup#Group stage|Group stage]]\n|Opponent\n|Result\n|-\n|align=left|{{fbw|NZL}}\n|2\u20131\n| style=\"background:#c1e0ff;\"|Match 1\n|align=left|{{fbw|PRK}}\n|2\u20130\n|-\n|align=left|{{fbw|MEX}}\n|4\u20130\n| style=\"background:#c1e0ff;\"|Match 2\n|align=left|{{fbw|COL}}\n|3\u20130\n|-\n|align=left|{{fbw|ENG}}\n|0\u20132\n| style=\"background:#c1e0ff;\"|Match 3\n|align=left|{{fbw|SWE}}\n|1\u20132\n|-\n|colspan=\"2\" align=center|\n<center>{{2011 FIFA Women's World Cup group tables|Group B|only_pld_pts=yes|showteam=JPN}}</center>\n|bgcolor=\"#c1e0ff\"|Final standing\n|colspan=\"2\" align=center|\n<center>{{2011 FIFA Women's World Cup group tables|Group C|only_pld_pts=yes|showteam=USA}}</center>\n|- valign=\"top\" bgcolor=\"#c1e0ff\"\n|Opponent\n|Result\n||[[2011 FIFA Women's World Cup knockout stage|Knockout stage]]\n|Opponent\n|Result\n|-\n|align=left|{{fbw|GER}}\n|1\u20130 ([[Overtime (sports)#Association football|a.e.t.]])\n|bgcolor=\"#c1e0ff\"|[[2011 FIFA Women's World Cup knockout stage#Quarterfinals|Quarterfinals]]\n|align=left|{{fbw|BRA}}\n|2\u20132 ([[Overtime (sports)#Association football|a.e.t.]]) (5\u20133 [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|pen.]])\n|-\n|align=left|{{fbw|SWE}}\n|3\u20131\n|bgcolor=\"#c1e0ff\"|[[2011 FIFA Women's World Cup knockout stage#Semifinals|Semifinals]]\n|align=left|{{fbw|FRA}}\n|3\u20131\n|}\n[[File:JapanvsEngland.jpg|thumb|right|Japan's group stage match against [[England women's national football team|England]] at [[SGL arena|Impuls Arena]]]]\n\nDespite being ranked 1st in the world by [[FIFA]],<ref name=\"fifa.com\">[https://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/ranking/lastranking/gender=f/fullranking.html#confederation=0&rank=533 FIFA/Coca-Cola Women's World Ranking], FIFA.com. Retrieved 11 August 2011</ref> the United States was the final team to qualify for the 2011 World Cup. After finishing third in the [[2010 CONCACAF Women's Gold Cup]], which serves as the [[CONCACAF]] qualifier, the United States was forced to defeat [[Italy women's national football team|Italy]] in a [[2011 FIFA Women's World Cup qualification (UEFA\u2013CONCACAF play-off)|Home and Away]] playoff.<ref>[http://www.concacaf.com/page/WGC/NewsDetail/0,,12813~1997374,00.html CONCACAF to host second leg of WWC playoff] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610223527/http://www.concacaf.com/page/WGC/NewsDetail/0,,12813~1997374,00.html |date=10 June 2011 }}, from concacaf.com, retrieved 14 July 2011</ref> Japan, ranked 4th,<ref name=\"fifa.com\"/>  qualified for the tournament by finishing third in the [[2010 AFC Women's Asian Cup]], which served as the [[Asian Football Confederation|AFC]] qualifier.\n\nOnce at the finals, the United States reached the knockout stage by finishing second in [[2011 FIFA Women's World Cup Group C|Group C]] behind [[Sweden women's national football team|Sweden]], the only team they lost to in group play. They advanced through the quarterfinals on a [[penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shootout]] with [[Brazil women's national football team|Brazil]], in which the United States footballer [[Abby Wambach]] scored an equalizer in the 122nd minute of the game \u2013 in stoppage time, the latest goal ever scored in Women's World Cup play,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gpb.org/news/2011/07/17/guts-goals-and-luck-will-win-the-world-cup|title=Guts, Goals And Luck Will Win The World Cup}}</ref> \u2013 to tie the game 2\u20132 and bring the game into a penalty shootout. The United States then defeated [[France women's national football team|France]] 3\u20131 to reach the final.<ref>[http://blog.chron.com/soccer/2011/07/as-is-custom-the-u-s-is-ready-for-the-semifinals-at-the-womens-world-cup/ As is custom, the U.S. is ready for the semifinals at the Women\u2019s World Cup]</ref>\n\nJapan reached the knockout stage by finishing second in [[2011 FIFA Women's World Cup Group B|Group B]] behind [[England women's national football team|England]], which was the only team to defeat Japan in group play.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/tables/_/league/fifa.wwc/women%27s-world-cup?cc=5901|title=Group Stage 2011 Table / Standings|publisher=ESPN Soccernet|accessdate=25 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/fixtures/_/league/fifa.wwc/fifa-womens-world-cup?cc=5901|title=WWC 2011 Fixtures & Results|publisher=ESPN Soccernet|accessdate=25 July 2011}}</ref> Japan then stunned the host nation, two-time defending champions Germany, 1\u20130 in extra time.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/07/10/sports/soccer/womens-world-cup-japans-late-goal-shocks-germany.html|title=Japan's Late Goal Shocks Germany|last=Longman|first=Jer\u00e9|work=The New York Times|date=9 July 2011|accessdate=25 July 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110710222622/http://www.nytimes.com/2011/07/10/sports/soccer/womens-world-cup-japans-late-goal-shocks-germany.html| archivedate= 10 July 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref> They then defeated Sweden 3\u20131 to reach the final match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/espnw/news-opinion/6767028/women-world-cup-japan-emotional-victory-sweden|title=For Japan, an emotional victory over Sweden|last=Gerstner|first=Joanne C.|publisher=ESPN|date=13 July 2011|accessdate=25 July 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Match==\n\n===Details===\n<section begin=Final />{{Football box\n|date={{Start date|2011|7|17|df=y}}\n|time=20:45 <noinclude>[[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]</noinclude>\n|team1={{fbw-rt|JPN}}\n|score={{score link|2011 FIFA Women's World Cup knockout stage#Final|2\u20132|2011 FIFA Women's World Cup Final}}\n|aet=yes\n|report=https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/matches/round=255989/match=300144437/index.html\n|team2={{fbw|USA}}\n|goals1=\n*[[Aya Miyama|Miyama]] {{goal|81}}\n*[[Homare Sawa|Sawa]] {{goal|117}}\n|goals2=\n*[[Alex Morgan|Morgan]] {{goal|69}}\n*[[Abby Wambach|Wambach]] {{goal|104}}\n|stadium=[[Waldstadion (Frankfurt)|Waldstadion]], [[Frankfurt]]\n|attendance=48,817<ref name=\"match report\">{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/mm/document/tournament/competition/01/47/65/78/32_0717_jpn-usa_fulltime.pdf |title=Match report \u2013 Final \u2013 Japan v USA |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |format=PDF |date=17 July 2011 |access-date=7 January 2020}}</ref>\n|referee=[[Bibiana Steinhaus]] ([[German Football Association|Germany]])\n|penalties1=\n*[[Aya Miyama|Miyama]] {{pengoal}}\n*[[Y\u016bki Nagasato|Nagasato]] {{penmiss}}\n*[[Mizuho Sakaguchi|Sakaguchi]] {{pengoal}}\n*[[Saki Kumagai|Kumagai]] {{pengoal}}\n|penaltyscore=3\u20131\n|penalties2=\n*{{penmiss}} [[Shannon Boxx|Boxx]]\n*{{penmiss}} [[Carli Lloyd|Lloyd]]\n*{{penmiss}